    <exprreq message="Must have 2 ranks in Sense Motive"><![CDATA[#skillranks[skSenseMot] >= 2]]></exprreq>
    <exprreq message="Must have 2 ranks in Diplomacy"><![CDATA[#skillranks[skDiplo] >= 2]]></exprreq>
    <exprreq message="Cannot have ranks in Bluff"><![CDATA[#skillranks[skBluff] <= 0]]></exprreq>
    <exprreq message="Cannot have ranks in Disguise"><![CDATA[#skillranks[skDisguise] <= 0]]></exprreq>
    <exprreq message="Cannot have ranks in Intimidate"><![CDATA[#skillranks[skIntim] <= 0]]></exprreq>
    <exprreq message="Cannot have ranks in Sleight of Hand"><![CDATA[#skillranks[skSleight] <= 0]]></exprreq>
    <exprreq message="Cannot have ranks in Stealth"><![CDATA[#skillranks[skStealth] <= 0]]></exprreq>
    <exprreq message="Must have 3 levels of Paladin"><![CDATA[#levelcount[Paladin] >= 3]]></exprreq>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuClaLim" name="Class Limitations" description="Justicars must follow a strict and rather unforgiving moral code.  Failure to follow these rules may result in the PC becoming a ex- Justicar.\n\n{b}Alignment:{/b} A Justicar must be lawful good. In addition to the strictures placed on a paladin, a Justicar must live by the following additional limitations:\n\n{b}Reject Cohorts and Henchmen:{/b} A Justicar may never gain followers, cohorts, henchmen, or hirelings. If, at the time of becoming a Justicar, the character has followers, cohorts, henchmen, or hirelings, he must renounce them and free them of their bonds of fealty or obligation. In addition, a Justicar may not hire men-at-arms. A Justicar may retain his special mount, if gained while a paladin. Once slain, however, a Justicar may not call a new mount. The only exception to this limitation is that a Justicar may retain his falcon familiar (see below) as long as he remains a Justicar. Willful disobedience of this principle results in the character becoming an ex-Justicar. Unintentional disobedience (accidentally obtaining a cohort because the cohort was enchanted to follow you, for example) requires {i}atonement{/i} and the Justicar must break the enchantment and rid himself of the cohort as quickly as possible. A simple offer by a prospective follower or cohort to follow you, if rejected, does not constitute disobedience.  This requirement does not prevent a Justicar from traveling with companions.\n\n{b}Reject Property:{/b} A Justicar may not own real property - land, buildings or other holdings, nor may he circumvent this by having agents or friends hold such property in his name. Willful disobedience of this principle results in the character becoming an ex-Justicar. Unintentional disobedience (inherited land, for example) requires {i}atonement{/i}. A gift of land, if rejected, does not constitute disobedience.\n\n{b}Reject Wealth:{/b} A Justicar may not possess more material wealth than is required to feed, clothe, and house his person in a modest fashion (usually no more than 100 gp). Willful disobedience of this principle results in the character becoming an ex-Justicar.  Unintentional disobedience (inheriting wealth, for example) requires {i}atonement{/i}. A gift of money or wealth, if rejected, does not constitute disobedience.\n\n{b}Reject Material Property and Magic:{/b} A Justicar may not carry more than his arms and armor, a pack with simple equipment, equipment for his mount, simple religious items, and simple clothes. He may not possess ornamental items. He may not possess magic items other than his arms and armor. He may, however, carry and use potions and scrolls created by priests of Thyr and Muir. Aside from arms and armor, all a Justicar need possess is faith in Muir. Willful disobedience of this principle results in the character becoming an ex-Justicar. Unintentional disobedience requires {i}atonement{/i}. Having a barred item hidden on you by an enemy, if unwanted, does not constitute disobedience if the Justicar immediately rejects the item once discovered.\n\n{b}Reject Disguise:{/b} As an embodiment of Truth, a Justicar may not thwart truth, regardless how noble the goal. Though he may tolerate it in others, a Justicar will not willingly disguise himself, accept magic intended to conceal or disguise his person or qualities, nor may he use protective magic based on disguise or hidden appearance. He will counsel against his companions using such tactics, though he will not split with persons who are otherwise good-aligned as a result of their use of such tactics. The Justicar simply will not take part in them. Willful disobedience of this principle results in the character becoming an ex-Justicar.  Unintentional disobedience (having a disguising spell cast upon you by a friend against your will) requires {i}atonement{/i}. Having a disguise or concealment spell cast upon you by an enemy, if unwanted, does not constitute disobedience if the Justicar immediately seeks to undo the disguise.\n\n{b}Reject Falsehood:{/b} A Justicar may not lie, regardless of how noble the goal. Lying means active deception. Standing silent or failing to answer a question is not lying. However, if a Justicar fails to answer a question because of an intent to deceive, he must do {i}atonement{/i}. Willful disobedience of this principle results in the character becoming an ex-Justicar. Unintentional disobedience (being magically compelled or otherwise forced to lie against your will, for example) requires {i}atonement{/i}. Because a Justicar embodies Truth, the GM is encouraged to demand the strictest compliance to this principle." compset="ClSpecial">
    <tag group="Helper" tag="SpecUp"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuExJust" name="Ex-Justicars" description="If a Justicar violates any of the strictures above, he becomes an ex-Justicar. He loses all Justicar spells and class features (including the service of the Justicar&apos;s falcon familiar, but not weapon, armor, and shield proficiencies). He may not progress any further in levels as a Justicar, nor can he ever regain his status as a Justicar. Muir is a strict and demanding goddess.\n\n{b}Torment:{/b} The above rules allow evil NPCs (or characters) to torment Justicars - attempting to give them wealth, magically disguising them against their will, etc. An evil creature can never cause a Justicar to become an ex-Justicar by such torment unless the Justicar willingly joins or fails to reject the evil character. At worst, such actions may require the Justicar to do {i}atonement{/i}. Note that in the case of such torment, a Justicar is free to attempt to slay the tormenting evil NPC prior to attempting to undo the source of the torment (breaking the spell on a charmed cohort, dismissing the {i}obscuring mist{/i} spell placed upon him, giving away treasure, etc.).  The only exception is lying. If a Justicar willfully lies, even to an evil opponent, he becomes an ex-Justicar." compset="ClSpecial">
    <tag group="Helper" tag="SpecUp"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuResIll" name="Resist Illusions" description="A Justicar gains a +4 divine bonus on Will saves against illusion magic. In addition, Justicars are allowed to save to disbelieve illusions without having to interact with the illusion, even if that is normally required to disbelieve the illusion." compset="ClSpecial">
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    <eval phase="Final" priority="20000"><![CDATA[
~ If we're not shown, just get out now
doneif (tagis[Helper.ShowSpec] <> 1)
~ if we've been replaced, get out now
doneif (tagis[Helper.SpcReplace] <> 0)

~Let's add a situational bonus to Will saves vs. Illusions
#situational[hero.child[svWill],"+4 divine bonus vs illusion magic",field[name].text]]]></eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuZonTru" name="Zone of Truth" description="Once per day for every three Justicar levels, a Justicar can cast the spell {i}zone of truth{/i} as a spell-like ability.  The ability functions as if cast by a caster of a level equal to the Justicar&apos;s total character level." compset="ClSpecial">
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="SpellLike"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Tracker"/>
    <tag group="Usage" tag="Day"/>
    <tag group="SpInfo" tag="spZoneTru2"/>
    <eval phase="PostLevel" priority="10000"><![CDATA[~ If we're not shown, just get out now
doneif (tagis[Helper.ShowSpec] <> 1)
~if we've been replaced, get out now
doneif (tagis[Helper.SpcReplace] <> 0)

~We have a number of charges equal to the number of times we appear

      field[listname].text = "Zone of Truth (" & field[xIndex].value & "/day)"

      field[trkMax].value += field[xCount].value]]></eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuEneEvi" name="Enemy of Evil" description="A Justicar gains a +2 divine bonus to attack and damage rolls against evil-aligned undead and outsiders." compset="ClSpecial">
    <fieldval field="actName" value="Attacking Undead/Outsider"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Activation"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    <eval phase="First" priority="10000"><![CDATA[
~ if we've been replaced, get out now
doneif (tagis[Helper.SpcReplace] <> 0)
~ If not activated get out now
doneif (field[abilActive].value <> 1)

~ Give +2H/D
hero.child[Attack].field[Bonus].value += 2
hero.child[Damage].field[tDamBonus].value += 2]]></eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuCelCom" name="Celestial Companion" description="A Justicar gains a celestial falcon - the holy animal of Muir - as a companion per the druid animal companion rules (see &quot;Druid&quot; in Chapter 3 of the Pathfinder Roleplaying Game).\n\n{b}Starting Statistics: Size{/b} Small; {b}Speed{/b} 10 ft., fly 80 ft. (average); {b}AC{/b} +1 natural armor; {b}Attack{/b} bite (1d4), 2 talons (1d4); {b}Ability Scores{/b} Str 10, Dex 17, Con 12, Int 2, Wis 14, Cha 10; {b}Special Attacks{/b} smite evil 1/day as a swift action (adds Cha bonus to attack rolls and damage bonus equal to HD against evil foes;smite persists until the target is dead or the celestial falcon rests); {b}Special Qualities{/b} darkvision 60 ft., low-light vision, DR and energy resistance per {i}Pathfinder Roleplaying Game Bestiary{/i} &quot;Celestial Creature&quot;, SR equal to class level +5 \n\n{b}4th-Level Advancement: Ability Scores{/b} Str +2, Con +2." compset="ClSpecial">
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuDisLie" name="Discern Lies" description="At 2nd level, a Justicar can {i}discern lies{/i} as the spell once per day and an additional time per day for every 3 Justicar levels thereafter (2 at 5th, 3 at 8th). The ability functions as if cast by a caster of a level equal to the Justicar&apos;s total character level." compset="ClSpecial">
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Tracker"/>
    <tag group="Usage" tag="Day"/>
    <tag group="SpInfo" tag="spDiscLie4"/>
    <eval phase="PostLevel" priority="10000"><![CDATA[~ If we're not shown, just get out now
doneif (tagis[Helper.ShowSpec] <> 1)
~if we've been replaced, get out now
doneif (tagis[Helper.SpcReplace] <> 0)

~We have a number of charges equal to the number of times we appear

      field[listname].text = "Discern Lies (" & field[xIndex].value & "/day)"

      field[trkMax].value += field[xCount].value]]></eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuShiTru" name="Shield of Truth" description="Beginning at 3rd level, a Justicar can invoke Muir&apos;s shield of truth once per day. Invoking this ability either enhances the Justicar&apos;s current shield or temporarily creates a supernatural shield for the Justicar to use. The shield has the following abilities: +2 divine truth bonus (if the shield is created, this is the only armor benefit it provides) and becomes a {i}blinding shield{/i} (see the &quot;Magic Items&quot; section in Chapter 15 of the Pathfinder Roleplaying Game), except the blinding effect only affects evil creatures. In addition, the shield radiates the effects of a {i}prayer{/i} spell for its duration. This ability lasts for 30 minutes. Shield of truth cannot be used in combination with either sword of courage or armor of honor until the Justicar gains the avatar ability." compset="ClSpecial">
    <fieldval field="actName" value="Shield of Truth"/>
    <fieldval field="trkMax" value="1"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Tracker"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Activation"/>
    <tag group="Usage" tag="Day"/>
    <eval phase="First" priority="10000"><![CDATA[~ If we're not shown, just get out now
     doneif (tagis[Helper.ShowSpec] = 0)

~Add a +2 Divine Truth bonus to AC that stacks with current shield]]></eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuMarJus" name="Mark of Justice" description="Beginning at 4th level, the Justicar gains the ability to pass holy judgment on others once per day and place a {i}mark of justice{/i} on persons so judged as the spell (but as a standard action). The ability functions as if cast by a caster of a level equal to the Justicar&apos;s total character level." compset="ClSpecial">
    <fieldval field="trkMax" value="1"/>
    <tag group="SpInfo" tag="spMarkJus4"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Tracker"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    <tag group="Usage" tag="Day"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuImmIll" name="Immunity to Illusions" description="Beginning at 5th level, a Justicar is immune to all illusions. A Justicar notes the presence of illusions but recognizes them for what they are and disbelieves them immediately and automatically." compset="ClSpecial">
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="SpecUp"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuSwoCou" name="Sword of Courage" description="Beginning at 6th level, a Justicar can invoke Muir&apos;s sword of courage once per day. Invoking this ability either enhances the Justicar&apos;s current sword or temporarily creates a supernatural magical bastard sword for the Justicar to use. The sword gains a +2 divine courage bonus to attack and damage rolls.  The sword also becomes a {i}holy{/i} weapon (see the &quot;Magic Items&quot; section in Chapter 15 of the Pathfinder Roleplaying Game) for its duration. In addition, the sword radiates {i}remove fear{/i} in a 30-foot radius for its duration (caster level equal to the Justicar&apos;s total character level). The ability lasts for 30 minutes. Sword of courage cannot be used in combination with either shield of truth or armor of honor until the Justicar gains the avatar ability." compset="ClSpecial">
    <fieldval field="trkMax" value="1"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Tracker"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    <tag group="Usage" tag="Day"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuScoEvi" name="Scourge of Evil" description="At 6th level, a Justicar gains an additional +1 divine bonus to attack and damage rolls and double the normal critical threat range against all evil-aligned creatures (of all types).  This ability stacks with the enemy of evil ability and the Improved Critical feat or {i}keen{/i} weapon quality if the Justicar has these as well." compset="ClSpecial">
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuTruSee" name="True Seeing" description="Beginning at 7th level, a Justicar can use {i}true seeing{/i} as the spell once per day. The ability functions as if cast by a caster of a level equal to the Justicar&apos;s total character level." compset="ClSpecial">
    <fieldval field="trkMax" value="1"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Tracker"/>
    <tag group="SpInfo" tag="spTrueSee6"/>
    <tag group="Usage" tag="Day"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuArmHon" name="Armor of Honor" description="Beginning at 8th level, a Justicar can invoke Muir&apos;s armor of honor once per day. Invoking this ability either enhances the Justicar&apos;s current armor or temporarily creates a suit of magical chainmail around the Justicar. The armor gains a +2 divine honor bonus to AC. The armor also has the qualities of {i}moderate fortification{/i}, {i}invulnerability{/i}, and {i}spell resistance (15){/i} (see the &quot;Magic Items&quot; section in Chapter 15 of the Pathfinder Roleplaying Game) for its duration. This ability lasts for 30 minutes. Armor of honor cannot be used in combination with either shield of truth or sword of courage until the Justicar gains the avatar ability." compset="ClSpecial">
    <fieldval field="trkMax" value="1"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Tracker"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    <tag group="Usage" tag="Day"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuHolWor" name="Holy Word" description="Beginning at 9th level, a Justicar can speak a {i}holy word{/i} as the spell once per day. The ability functions as if cast by a caster of a level equal to the Justicar&apos;s total character level." compset="ClSpecial">
    <fieldval field="trkMax" value="1"/>
    <tag group="SpInfo" tag="spHolyWor7"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Tracker"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    <tag group="Usage" tag="Day"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuAvatar" name="Avatar" description="At 10th level, a Justicar can use shield of truth, sword of courage, and armor of honor at the same time up to once per week. When all three powers are invoked at the same time it seems as if a spectral figure of Muir herself overlaps the body of the Justicar and mimics his every movement. In combat against evil creatures the figure of Muir becomes even more apparent. In addition to allowing all three powers to operate in unison, when a Justicar becomes an Avatar of Muir he is treated as if under the effects of a {i}greater heroism{/i} spell (caster level equal to the Justicar&apos;s total character level) for the duration of the ability. The avatar ability lasts only so long as all three abilities - shield of truth, sword of courage, and armor of honor - are in effect at the same time." compset="ClSpecial">
    <fieldval field="trkMax" value="1"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Tracker"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    <tag group="Usage" tag="Week"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cJMuDemBan" name="Demon-bane" description="At 10th level, a Justicar becomes an evilkilling machine. His critical threat range is doubled against evil undead and outsiders. This ability stacks with both the scourge of evil ability (see above) and the Improved Critical feat or {i}keen{/i} weapon quality if the Justicar has these as well." compset="ClSpecial">
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
